text=(:if [ authgroup @tas || authgroup @admins || equal {$Author} '' ]:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=edit|Edit this page]] \\%0aStatus: {GradebookArticles.{$Name}$:Status} %0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!{$:Category}]]%0a%0a!Amami Ōshima language%0a%0a:Author: savannah%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAmami Ōshima language%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe Amami language, also known as Amami Ōshima or Ōshima, is a language spoken in the Japanese Amami Islands, classified as "definitely endangered" by UNESCO (1, 3). Although the number of native speakers is unknown, it is known that the language is spoken mostly among elderly people (1). %0a%0aThe Amami language is recognized as a dialect in Japan, not a language. The main factor contributing to the language's endangerment is Japan's monolingual ideology that suppresses the expansion of other languages (1,2). As a result of Japan's language policy, Japanese is usually the first language of younger generations (1). Moreover, Standard Japanese has more economic and cultural power, so it is unlikely for younger generations to choose to speak or learn Ōshima (1). Because of these reasons, there are an estimated 10,000 speakers of the northern variety and 2,000 speakers of the southern variety of the Amami language as of 2015 (1).%0a%0aAccording to Heinrich, attempts at the revitalization of languages in the Ryukyu Islands have been made, and early efforts concentrated in the northern Amami-Oshima island group but later shifted to other languages (4). Moreover, even after years of recognition of the languages as endangered by UNESCO, there still has not been much change on the side of the Japanese government (5).%0a%0a1. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amami_%25C5%258Cshima_language#cite_note-e18-1%0a2.https://www.researchgate.net/publication/287069712_Language_policy_in_Japan_The_challenge_of_change#:~:text=This%2520national%2520monolingual%2520ideology%2520requires,the%2520north%2520(Gottlieb%25202012)%2520.a %0a3. https://www.endangeredlanguages.com/lang/10377#sources_popup_wrapper%0a4. https://apjjf.org/-Patrick-Heinrich/1596/article.pdf%0a5. https://academic.oup.com/book/38834/chapter/337725138%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:elseif [ equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:andrewid} '' || equal {Profiles.{$Author}$:section} '' ] :)%0a%0aYou must enter your andrew ID and section before submitting an expansion. %0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a%0a----%0a(:if equal {$Author} {$:Author}:)%0a!!Change article category%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#changearticlecategory:)%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a%0a(:Section: A:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)%0a(:Title: Amami Ōshima language:)
